^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|At least as of a few years ago, the most common method for bidding after a takeout double was as follows:

1) New suits at the 1 level are forcing and unlimited (same as if there were no takeout double)|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


AT|

2) New suits at the 2 level and above are weak, and show less than 10 points. (This principle is not understood by many less experienced  players.)|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


AT|

3) 2 level raises in the majors typically show 6-9 with 3-card support; 3 level raises show 4-card support and less than a limit raise.|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


AT|

4) 2 level raises in the minors typically show 6-9 with 4-card support; 3 level raises show 5-card support and less than a limit raise.|
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


AT|

5) 2NT is Jordan 2NT, showing 4+-card support and at least limit raise strength (both in the majors and minors).|
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


AT|

6) Redouble shows 10+ points and denies 4+ card support.|
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


AT|

I think there is a simpler way to play, and that is what I use. With 10+ points, you redouble with less than 4-card support and bid Jordan 2NT with 4+ card support. Any other bid denies 10 points and is not forcing (including new suit bids).|
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


AT|

Having said that, playing my methods on the hand we just played, I technically should have bid 2N. If you play the common methods, then I could also have bid 1H, which is forcing.|
PG| ***** 36 ***** |


AT|

I suspect, in this deal, most of the time it would go 1D-P-1H-P-1N-P-3N, and be down 2 on a club lead. Another possible auction is 1D-1S (if Howard were East)-dbl-2S-P-P-3N. And then it might make if I can sneak a heart in before they discover their 5 club tricks or they pitch some clubs on diamonds. Let us look at the hand with the first bidding cycle.|
